Benchmark: Optimal information disclosure with identical sellers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I start by considering the case of identical sellers, that is where 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is a singleton.
 The next proposition establishes that any Pareto-optimal outcome (in seller
 profits-buyer surplus space) is implementable by a disclosure policy.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:Pareto-frontier"

\end_inset

Suppose the sellers are identical.
 Then for any Pareto-optimal outcome 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,U)$
\end_inset

, there is a disclosure policy that implements it.
 Furthermore, an optimal disclosure policy has a binary structure.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The proof relies on the Revelation Principle.
 Since there is one seller type and two actions, it suffices to consider
 only disclosure policies that send two signals, where a signal is an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

action recommendation
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (in this case, either 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

accept
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

reject
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) .
 With such a binary signaling structure, the seller dynamic optimization
 problem reduces to a static optimization problem.
 Indeed, since there is only one signal with a recommendation to accept,
 there is only one type of acceptable buyers.
 All profitable buyers are the same, and there is no return to cream-skimming.
 Since a Pareto-optimal outcome is feasible (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $V\geq0$
\end_inset

), sellers have an incentive to follow the platform's recommendation to
 accept.
 For the details of the proof, see Appendix
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "proof:id-sellers-Pareto-frontier"

\end_inset

